{"questionId":"27624","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>Let&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>f</mi><mfenced><mi>x</mi></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>x</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>3</mn></math>, for&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>x</mi><mo>∈</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">ℝ</mi></math>.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p>The graph of a linear function <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>h</mi></math> is perpendicular to the graph of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>f</mi></math> and passes through&nbsp;the point <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>)</mo></math> . Find an expression for <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>h</mi><mo>(</mo><mi>x</mi><mo>)</mo></math>.</p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p>gradient is&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac></math>&nbsp;&nbsp;(may be seen in function)<em><strong>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; (A1)</strong></em></p>\n<p>attempt to substitute <strong>their</strong> gradient and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>)</mo></math>&nbsp;into any form of equation for straight line<em><strong>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; (M1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>y</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mfenced><mrow><mi>x</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfenced></math>&nbsp; OR&nbsp;&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mo>·</mo><mfenced><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfenced><mo>+</mo><mi>c</mi></math></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>h</mi><mfenced><mi>x</mi></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mfenced><mrow><mi>x</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfenced><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mfenced><mrow><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mi>x</mi><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mn>5</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac></mrow></mfenced></math>&nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;</strong></em><em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><em><strong>[3 marks]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"27624","referenceCode":"22N.1.SL.TZ0.1b","subjectId":"50-dp-mathematics-analysis-and-approaches","title":"The graph of a linear function h is perpendicular to the graph of f and passes through the point (-1, 2) . Find an expression for h(x).","paper":"1","level":"SL","questionNumber":"b","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 3]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 2—Functions","Topic 2—Functions","SL 2.1—Equations of straight lines, parallel and perpendicular"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}